<h3>Triage process
</h3>

<p>In the new process the first thing we did was add a triage step, to shape requests for work, aligning them to the wider strategy, defining the problem to solve and the desired outcomes and success measures. 
</p>

<figure id="figure9">
<img class="half" src="/images/posts/is-this-service-design/triage-process.png" loading="lazy" alt="Triage process">
<figcaption>Triage process</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Triage questions:
</p>

<ul class="unordered-list">
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">What is the problem to be solved
</li>
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">Short background to the problem space, team etc 
</li>
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">What are the expected outcomes
</li>
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">What work has been done to date?
</li>
    <li class="unordered-list__list-item">How will we measure success?
</li>
</ul>

<p>This should help us to get service design involved further upstream, and to create consistency across the programme, removing any duplication and contradictions.
</p>

<p>Then we split work into 3 lanes: 
</p>

<ol class="ordered-list">
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">Discovery, because there is a well defined problem to solve </li>
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">Continuous improvement, we have a valid problem but the work is better suited to being added to an existing teams backlog 
</li>
    <li class="unordered-list__list-item">Exploration, this problem is too big for us to solve all at once </li>
</ol>

<p>The first 2 are pretty self explanatory, the third one can be a bit more controversial. 
</p>


<p>Exploration or pre-discovery has a reputation for adding time and cost to a project without adding much value. I’ve definitely seen this happen and we definitely dont always need this phase. But if we have a statement as broad as “How might we better facilitate trade” we need space to break the problem down into more manageable chunks.
</p>

