<h2>Summary
</h2>

<p>Designing and delivering better services is about having a shared service vision and outcomes, aligning around problems to solve, and continuously measuring value. This isn’t something that succeeds or fails based on the inclusion of any individual role. 
</p>

<p>Simply having a service designer won’t remove any of the barriers to good service design. Most of the work is aligning and working together with the right people in the right space, whoever and wherever that might be.
</p>

<p>Some of the key takeaways have been: 
</p>

<ul class="unordered-list">
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">there is a constant balancing act between improving what exists and planning for what could exist
</li>
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">before we can really progress we need to design our internal structures and design a process for how work is created and delivered 
</li>
</ul>


{# <p>In a way it’s a chicken and egg situation. To design a whole service you first need to design how an organisation works. To re-design an organisation you need an understanding of your services. 
</p> #}





























